          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Rally against embargo</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-23-1.jpg" alt="Rally against embargo" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The Cuban government and citizens <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-dec-2024-1-protested" target="_blank">protested</a> in front of the U.S. Embassy on Friday over the trade sanctions. President Miguel Díaz-Canel and former leader Raúl Castro led the protest. The protestors are calling for an end to the U.S. trade embargo, which is blamed for the severe economic challenges Cuba faces, and for an end to U.S. interference. The Cuban government argues that the embargo has disabled the country’s economy, worsening shortages and limiting growth.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">President Díaz-Canel criticized Biden for upholding Trump’s policies instead of removing them, including designating Cuba a state sponsor of terrorism, which isolates it financially. While US sanctions play a role in Cuba’s worsening economy, some also say they are often overused as an excuse to cover up the government's failings. The Cuban president has, however, come out before to take some <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-dec-2024-2-partial-blame" target="_blank">partial blame</a>. The situation will likely not improve with Trump’s return to the White House.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>


