          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Playing with fire</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-23-2.jpg" alt="Playing with fire" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">China has <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-dec-2024-3-condemned-the-united-states" target="_blank">condemned the United States</a> after it announced a $571.3 million military aid to Taiwan. Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs called it “dangerous moves that undermine peace and stability.” China also added that the US is crossing a major redline. Tensions have been heating up more recently, with China conducting <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-dec-2024-4-military-activities" target="_blank">military activities</a> near Taiwan, including large-scale maritime drills and regular aerial and naval operations.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">President Joe Biden announced shortly before leaving office that the United States had approved $571.3 million in military aid for Taiwan. The package includes defense articles, services, and training, though specific details remain undisclosed. This follows a $567 million package authorized just three months ago. Taiwan received 38 tanks earlier this week, its first new tank in 30 years. Taiwan thanked the U.S. for its support and reaffirmed its commitment to peace and stability in the Taiwan Strait.​</p>
        </mj-text>
