          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Who are the Houthis?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-23-3.jpg" alt="foundations" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-dec-2024-11-houthis" target="_blank">Houthis</a> (formerly known as Ansar Allah) are a militant group from northern Yemen. They originated in the 1990s as a movement advocating for the rights of Yemen's Zaydi Shia minority but evolved into a powerful insurgent force. They took their name from its late founder Hussein al-Houthi and is now led by his brother Abdul Malik al-Houthi.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">They are one of Iran's proxies to help it fight against Israel, and they also serve as a proxy for its conflict with Saudi Arabia. Although Iran claims only to be supporting them politically and not economically, specialists say it would be impossible for them to have advanced as much as they have without military and economic support from Iran.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">In 2014, they took over Yemen's capital, Sanaa, and later expanded their control across the country. They are engaged in an ongoing civil war with the internationally recognized Yemeni government, which is supported by a Saudi-led coalition. They gained more international traction in 2023 when they started attacking ships in the Red Sea for revenge on Gaza. ​</p>
        </mj-text>
